[6] USA (Tennessee)
Date: Tue 13 May 2014
Source: WBBJ TV News [edited]
http://www.wbbjtv.com/news/local/Ask-An-Expert-Measles-Cases-in-Madison-County-259149401.html


We spoke with Shanna Shearon, the Regional Epidemiologist at Jackson-Madison County Regional Health Department on Monday [12 May 2014] shortly after learning about the [measles] cases. Some of her answers to questions about these measles cases are below.

"We are investigating 2 possible measles cases in Madison County. Contacts have been made. All procedures have been followed. Everything has been done with those possible cases and their contacts. Everyone has been prophylaxed. That's what we need to do right now. We are kind of waiting and trying to educate as we can."

"People who are exposed to positive measles cases can actually get post-exposure prophylaxis, which is the MMR shot up to 72 hours after being exposed. Most people who are immunized are supposed to get 2 doses, which is what gives you immunity."

"It's always a good thing to be immunized against these preventable diseases that we are seeing a rise in. You can talk to a physician or contact the health department about setting up an MMR. You can get exposed by someone who is infectious with the measles. It's highly contagious, so you have to be careful with that."

"Measles begins with a fever, fatigue and a cough. You will have a rash a few days after the symptoms start. A lot of times, these diseases come back, especially with international travel, and then the people who are not immune to the disease [can catch it]."

