Oceania
-------
[15] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Fri 16 May 2014
Source: The Courier Mail [edited]
http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/measles-alert-at-stuartholme-catholic-girls-school/story-fnihsrf2-1226920797447


A measles scare at a Perth hospital has left hundreds of people potentially exposed to the virus. Students at Brisbane Catholic girls' school Stuartholme will forfeit all netball games today [16 May 2014] due to a case of measles at the school. A message posted on the Stuartholme School website yesterday [15 May 2014] said Queensland Health's Metro North Public Health Unit had been notified of one case "associated with the school." It said the person had been at school between 5-12 May 2014, while unaware they were infectious.

"The case was not aware they were infectious at this time, and the disease can be passed on before a person becomes unwell," it said. "This is an important public health matter, and we ask for parent co-operation with the school and Queensland Health to help prevent the further spread of measles."

The unit said the school was taking the following recommendations to prevent the spread of measles:
- Students and staff who are not immune to measles, that is they do not have 2 documented doses of a measles-containing vaccine or other evidence of measles immunity, should be excluded from school and remain isolated at home until 30 May 2014 (with the date to be revised if there are further measles cases).
- Students and staff who have a previous documented single dose of a measles-containing vaccine may return to school upon receipt of a 2nd documented dose; however, these students/staff should be restricted from attending events external to the school (e.g. interschool sport) until 30 May 2014.
- Any student or staff who has a condition that suppresses the immune system (regardless of vaccination status) should be excluded from school and remain isolated at home until 30 May 2014 (with the date to be revised if there are further measles cases).
- Pregnant staff who do not have 2 documented doses of a measles-containing vaccine or other evidence of measles immunity should be excluded from school and remain isolated at home until 30 May 2014 (with the date to be revised if there are further measles cases).
- Boarding students will be assessed on a case-by-case basis for advice on isolation and activity restrictions, but the use of public transport, including air travel, is strongly discouraged.
- Anyone who develops symptoms of measles in the next few weeks, as described in the measles fact sheet should remain away from school and seek medical advice. This includes people who are considered immune to measles as there is a small possibility they may still develop the disease. Please phone your doctor before you see them so that appropriate precautions can be taken to limit the spread of the disease in the medical setting.

Western Districts Netball Association last night [15 May 2014] said all Stuartholme teams would be forfeiting their games today. Queensland Health said there had been regular measles outbreaks in the state since September 2013, with many people contracting the highly infectious illness while overseas. In March 2014, a Sunshine Coast traveller caught the infection in Viet Nam.

Measles symptoms can include a fever, tiredness, coughing and runny nose followed by a red spotty rash and sore eyes. Queensland Health said these symptoms usually become more severe over the 1st 3 days.

[Byline: Kate McKenna]

